-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: EABL, Mauritius Leasing, Naiade Resorts Move
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 2010-12-24T13:44:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-24/sub-saharan-african-equities-report-eabl-mauritius-leasing-are-active.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped two
days of gains, falling 0.2 percent to 1,925.63 by the 1:30 p.m.
close in Port Louis.  The drop pared the gauge’s increase this
year to 16 percent.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index  climbed 0.3 percent to 77.63 by the
3 p.m. close in Nairobi. The measure has risen 33 percent in
2010. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  dropped 0.1
percent to 24,686.6 at 11:59 a.m. in Lagos, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index 
closed 0.1 percent weaker at 860.99 by 12 p.m. in Windhoek. The
 Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  rose for the first time in
five days, climbing 1.3 percent to 7,271.76.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  East African Breweries Ltd.  (EABL KN), 43 percent owned by
Diageo Plc, fell the most since Dec. 7, retreating 4 shillings,
or 1.9 percent, to 205 shillings. The Commission for Monopolies
and Prices said it will monitor the company to prevent abuse of
its monopoly position the Standard newspaper reported, citing a
report by the commission. EABL, as the company is known, has a
market share of 90 percent and exclusive agreements with
companies on the value chain, the Nairobi-based newspaper said.  Mauritius Leasing Co.  (MLC MP), which provides leasing
facilities for moveable assets and equipment, fell the most
since at least May 2004, dropping 1.4 rupees, or 16 percent, to
7.2 rupees. The company doesn’t plan to stop trading shares on
the exchange and is looking to restructure its operations,
l’Express reported today, citing Javed Bolah, the head of
communications at the British American Investment Co., Mauritius
Leasing’s parent company.  “The drop is seen as a realistic correction after the
exaggerated surge in prices noticed in the past weeks which
arose from speculation of a possible delisting of the company
from the market,” Cim Stockbrokers Ltd. wrote in an e-mailed
report to clients dated today.  Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
dropped the most since Nov. 16, retreating 1.2 rupees, or 4.7
percent, to 24.3 rupees on speculation its 11 percent advance
yesterday was overdone. “It’s the outcome of profit-taking by
investors’, Imrith Ramtohul, head of investment at Mauritius
Union Assurance Ltd., said in an e-mailed response to questions
from Port Louis.  To contact the reporters on this story:
